					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/psul" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2156983); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2156983&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251321" alt="psul" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2156983)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/psul" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2156983); return false;" >psul</a></span> <span class="odate time_1456390200 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">25 Feb 2016 08:50</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2462967">
									

<p>This got better as it went along. A lot of it, especially the first section, felt very expository (I'm not sure who is making the quoted comments, but they didn't feel natural). And several of the characters still feel one- or two-dimensional, although that's natural for the episode that's introducing them.</p>
<p>The mixed-media nature of the log works in its favour (although I can't work out why Enriquez wrote his goodbye note after having left!), and seeing the MTF through Manu 13's eyes is both interesting and (as others have said) a good way to push Manu's characterisation.</p>
<p>And the last conversation (plus some of Qasim's speech) started to feel more natural - less caught up in scene-setting, and more in character interactions, which shows off the potential of the group. I'm neutral on this one, but with interest piqued for what's to come.</p>

							</div>

								
					
