				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/hercules-rockefeller" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2314402); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2314402&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251321" alt="Hercules Rockefeller" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2314402)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/hercules-rockefeller" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2314402); return false;" >Hercules Rockefeller</a></span> <span class="odate time_1458353936 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">19 Mar 2016 02:18</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2475354">
									

<p>Wow, the way the article started i didn't think I'd like it (the first part felt a bit too much like an info dump and I wasn't a fan of the character quotes), but then you really pulled me in with the Manu character; somehow you managed to make him likeable and interesting and creepy all at once - I was reminded a little of Bishop from Aliens (whom I like a lot), only much more innocent and child-like. Easily one of the best characters in the contest.</p>
<p>To be honest I was surprised to see you involved in this kind of project - the sci-fi, futuristic aspect seemed like a huge departure from your usual, understated style. But you pulled it off nicely, while still managing to make the article your own. Well done.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Minor&nbsp;nitpicks</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Hide</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>1. Not sure what the point of the game at the end was. What it all just a set-up for the Manu joke (about borrowing a shirt from someone)? If so, I felt it ran a bit long, and I didn't really get what the MTF members were supposed to be doing with the game - what was the context? was it an exercise? or just for fun?</p>
<p>2. I don't think people will still be using paper in 150 years (let's face it, we barely use it as it is); even if they did, though, you definitely wouldn't find any on a spaceship - why take up more space/use up more fuel for paper when you can just use tablets, or whatever their equivalent will be 150 years from now? All of that to say, I think that the handwritten notes wouldn't be something you'd find on that ship. Most likely Manu would just be showing digital text files that had been deleted from the MTF members' devices. (you could still show them in images, though, as screencaps showing text readouts)</p>
<p>3. This is really minor, but the pictures of the objects were clearly taken on earth (sunlight is visible in most of them), when they're supposed to have been taken onboard a ship. I suggest maybe messing around with the brightness and hue in photoshop until they look more space-y. (I can help with this, if you're interested)</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Plus oned!</p>

							</div>

								
					
